The spread of culture and language in human populations is |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
explained by two alternative models: the demic diffusion model, |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
which involves mass movement of people; and the cultural |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
diffusion model, which refers to cultural impact between popu- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
lations and involves limited genetic exchange between them1. The |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mechanism of the peopling of Europe has long been debated, a |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
key issue being whether the diffusion of agriculture and language |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
from the Near East was concomitant with a large movement of |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
farmers1–3. Here we show, by systematically analysing Y-chromo- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
some and mitochondrial DNAvariation in Han populations, that |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the pattern of the southward expansion of Han culture is |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
consistent with the demic diffusion model, and that males played |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
a larger role than females in this expansion. The Han people, who |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
all share the same culture and language, exceed 1.16 billion (2000 |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
census), and are by far the largest ethnic group in the world. The |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
expansion process of Han culture is thus of great interest to |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
researchers in many fields. |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
According to the historical records, the Hans were descended |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
from the ancient Huaxia tribes of northern China, and the Han |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
culture (that is, the language and its associated cultures) expanded |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
into southern China—the region originally inhabited by the |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
southern natives, including those speaking Daic, Austro-Asiatic |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
and Hmong-Mien languages—in the past two millennia4,5. Studies |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
on classical genetic markers and microsatellites show that the |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Han people, like East Asians, are divided into two genetically |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
differentiated groups, northern Han and southern Han6,8, separated |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
approximately by the Yangtze river9. Differences between these |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
groups in terms of dialect and customs have also been noted10. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Such observations seem to support a mechanism involving |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
primarily cultural diffusion and assimilation (the cultural diffusion |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
model) in Han expansion towards the south. However, the sub- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
stantial sharing of Y-chromosome and mitochondrial lineages |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
between the two groups11,12 and the historical records describing |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the expansion of Han people5 contradict the cultural diffusion |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
model hypothesis of Han expansion. In this study, we aim to |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
examine the alternative hypothesis; that is, that substantial popu- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
lation movements occurred during the expansion of Han culture |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(the demic diffusion model). |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
To test this hypothesis, we compared the genetic profiles of |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
southern Hans with their two parental population groups: northern |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Hans and southern natives, which include the samples of Daic, |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Hmong-Mien and Austro-Asiatic speaking populations currently |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
residing in China, and in some cases its neighbouring countries. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Genetic variation in both the non-recombining region of the Y |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
chromosome (NRY) and mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA)13–16 were |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
surveyed in 28 Han populations from most of the provinces in |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
China (see Fig. 1 and Supplementary Table 1 for details). |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
On the paternal side, southern Hans and northern Hans share |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
similar frequencies of Y-chromosome haplogroups (Supplementary |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Table 2), which are characterized by two haplogroups carrying the |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
M122-C mutations (O3-M122 and O3e-M134) that are prevalent |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
in almost all Han populations studied (mean and range: 53.8%, |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
37–71%; 54.2%, 35–74%, for northern and southern Hans, respect- |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ively). Haplogroups carrying M119-C (O1* and O1b) and/or |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
M95-T (O2a* and O2a1) (following the nomenclature of the Y |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Chromosome Consortium) which are prevalent in southern |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
natives, are more frequent in southern Hans (19%, 3–42%) than |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
in northern Hans (5%, 1–10%). In addition, haplogroups |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
O1b-M110, O2a1-M88 and O3d-M7, which are prevalent in |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
southern natives 17, were only observed in some southern Hans |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(4% on average), but not in northern Hans. Therefore, the contri- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
bution of southern natives in southern Hans is limited, if we assume |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
that the frequency distribution of Y lineages in southern natives |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
represents that before the expansion of Han culture that started |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
2,000 yr ago5. The results of analysis of molecular variance |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(AMOVA) further indicate that northern Hans and southern |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Hans are not significantly different in their Y haplogroups |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(FST = 0.006, P > 0.05), demonstrating that southern Hans bear |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
a high resemblance to northern Hans in their male lineages. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
On the maternal side, however, the mtDNA haplogroup distri- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
bution showed substantial differentiation between northern Hans |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
and southern Hans (Supplementary Table 3). The overall frequen- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
