MBE and MRH refer to the statistics described in refs 20 and 19, respectivey. The standard error |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
of MBE was obtained by bootstrap with 1,000 repications. The proportions of contribution from |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
northern Hans were estimated using northern Hans and southern natives as the parenta |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
popuations of the southern Hans. It was assumed that the alele frequency in the southern |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
natives remained unchanged before and after the admixture, which started about 2,000 yr ago, |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
and the genetic exchange between northern Hans and southern natives has been limited. In |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
fact, the gene flow from northern Hans to southern natives has been larger than that from |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
southern natives to northern Hans; therefore, the leve of admixture presented in this tabe is |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
underestimated and is without proper adjustment. The demic expansion of Han woud have |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
been more pronounced than was observed in this study. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
NATURE | VOL 431|16 SEPTEMBER 2004 | www.nature.com/nature	©2004 Nature Publishing Group	303 |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
letters to nature |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-1 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
lation admixture in southern Hans. The proportions of northern |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Han contribution (M) in southern Hans showed a clinal geographic |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
pattern, which decreases from north to south. The Ms in southern |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Hans are positively correlated with latitude (r2 = 0.569, P < 0.01) |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
for mtDNA, but are not significant for the Y chromosome |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(r2 = 0.072, P > 0.05), because the difference of Ms in the paternal |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
lineage among southern Hans is too small to create a statistically |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
significant trend. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
We provide two lines of evidence supporting the demic diffusion |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
hypothesis for the expansion of Han culture. First, almost all Han |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
populations bear a high resemblance in Y-chromosome haplogroup |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
distribution, and the result of principal component analysis indi- |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cated that almost all Han populations form a tight cluster in their Y |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
chromosome. Second, the estimated contribution of northern Hans |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
to southern Hans is substantial in both paternal and maternal |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
lineages and a geographic cline exists for mtDNA. It is noteworthy |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
that the expansion process was dominated by males, as is shown by a |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
greater contribution to the Y-chromosome than the mtDNA from |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
northern Hans to southern Hans. A sex-biased admixture pattern |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
was also observed in Tibeto-Burman-speaking populations22. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
According to the historical records, there were continuous south- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
ward movements of Han people due to warfare and famine in the |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
north, as illustrated by three waves of large-scale migrations (Fig. 1). |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Aside from these three waves, other smaller southward migrations |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
also occurred during almost all periods in the past two millennia. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Figure 2 Principal component plot. a, b, Plots are of Y-chromosome (a) and mtDNA (b) |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
haplogroup frequency. Population groups: H-M, Hmong-Mien; DAC, Daic; A-A, Austro- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Asiatic; SH, southern Han; NH, northern Han. |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Our genetic observation is thus in line with the historical accounts. |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
The massive movement of the northern immigrants led to a change |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
in genetic makeup in southern China, and resulted in the demo- |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
graphic expansion of Han people as well as their culture. Except for |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
these massive population movements, gene flow between northern |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Hans, southern Hans and southern natives also contributed to |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the admixture which shaped the genetic profile of the extant |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
populations. ❑ |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-2 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_continue
Methods |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_larger xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Samples |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Blood samples of 871 unrelated anonymous individuals from 17 Han populations were |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
collected across China. Genomic DNA was extracted by the phenol-chloroform method. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
By integrating the additional data obtained from the literatures on the Y chromosome and |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
on mtDNA variation, the final sample sizes for analysis expanded to 1,289 individuals |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(23 Han populations) for the Y chromosome and 1,119 individuals (23 Han populations) |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
for mtDNA. These samples encompass most of the provinces in China (Fig. 1 and |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Supplementary Table 1). |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Genetic markers |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Thirteen bi-allelic Y-chromosome markers, YAP, M15, M130, M89, M9, M122, M134, |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
M119, M110, M95, M88, M45 and M120 were typed by polymerase chain reaction- |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
restriction-fragment length polymorphism methods11. These markers are highly |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
informative in East Asians23 and define 13 haplogroups following the Y Chromosome |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Consortium nomenclature24. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
The HVS-1 of mtDNA and eight coding region variations, 9-bp deletion, 10397 AluI, |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_new
5176 AluI, 4831 HhaI, 13259 HincII, 663 HaeIII, 12406 HpaI and 9820 HinfI were |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
sequenced and genotyped as in our previous report22. Both the HVS-1 motif and the |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
coding region variations were used to infer haplogroups following the phylogeny of East |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Asian mtDNAs18. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Data analysis |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Population relationship was investigated by principal component analysis, which was |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
conducted using mtDNA and Y-chromosome haplogroup frequencies and SPSS10.0 |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
software (SPSS Inc.). The genetic difference between northern and southern Hans was |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tested by AMOVA25, using ARLEQUIN software26. ADMIX 2.0 (ref. 27) and LEADMIX21 |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
software were used to estimate the level of admixture of the northern Hans and southern |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
natives in the southern Han populations, using two different statistics19–20. The selection of |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
parental populations is critical for appropriate estimation of admixture proportion28,29 |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
and we were careful to minimize bias by using large data sets across East Asia. In this |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
analysis, the average haplogroup frequencies (for Y-chromosome or mtDNA markers, |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
respectively) of northern Hans (arithmetic mean of 10 northern Hans) were taken for the |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
northern parental population. The frequency of southern natives was estimated by the |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
average of three groups including Austro-Asiatic (NRY, 6 populations; mtDNA, 5 |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
populations), Daic (NRY, 22 populations; mtDNA, 11 populations) and Hmong-Mien |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(NRY, 18 populations; mtDNA, 14 populations). The geographic pattern of Han |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
populations was revealed by the linear regression analysis of admixture proportion against |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the latitudes of samples1,3. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
